 and Jain examples in India, Nepal, and North America, the essays in this volume, written by renowned scholars of religion, explore how the intentional, conscious, and public invention or alteration of ritual can effect dramatic social transformation, whether in dethroning a Nepali king or sanctioning same-sex marriage. Ritual Innovation shows how the very idea of ritual as a conservative force misreads the history of religion by overlooking ritual's inherent creative potential and its adaptability to new contexts and circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRitualzSouth AsiavCongresses. 0aRitualzSouth Asia. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh1 aAllocco, Amy L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllocco, Amy L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaltutis, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaulagain, Nawaraj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, Corinne G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurayappah, Sudharshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunn, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLocklin, Reid B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMocko, Anne T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPennington, Brian K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPennington, Brian K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPreston, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela